{|{{Infobox ship begin |infobox caption= |italic title=}} <!-- commercial vessels --><!----> {{Infobox ship image |Ship image=<!-->Cemfjord2.jpg<--> |Ship caption=<!-->The Cemfjord before it sank.<--> }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country=[[Cyprus]] |Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Cyprus|civil}} |Ship name=*''Margareta'' (1984–2004) *''Cemfjord'' (2004–15) |Ship owner=*Thekla Schepers KG, Haren (1984–95) *Shark Shipping Co, NV, Willemstad (1995–2008) *Arouno Shipping Co Ltd, Limassol (2008–15) |Ship operator=*Margareta & Co, Haren (1984–95) *Brise Bereederungs GmbH & Co KG, Hamburg (1995–2015) |Ship registry=*{{flagicon|West Germany}} [[Haren, Germany|Haren]], [[West Germany]] (1984–89) *{{flagicon|Germany}} Haren, Germany (1989–2008) *{{flagicon|Cyprus}} [[Limassol]], Cyprus (2008–15) |Ship route= |Ship ordered= |Ship builder=Detlef Hegemann Rolandwerft, Bremen |Ship original cost= |Ship yard number=126 |Ship way number= |Ship laid down=15 February 1984 |Ship launched=31 August 1984 |Ship completed=November 1984 |Ship christened= |Ship acquired= |Ship maiden voyage= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service=2 January 2015 |Ship identification=*{{IMO Number|8403569}} *Callsign DCOG (1984–2008), P3ZG9 (2008–15) |Ship fate=Sank with all hands lost |Ship status= |Ship notes= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class= |Ship type= |Ship tonnage=*{{GT|1850}} *{{DWT|2327}} *661 [[net tonnage|NT]] |Ship displacement= |Ship length={{convert|83.13|m|ftin}} overall |Ship beam= {{convert|11.34|m|ftin}} |Ship height={{convert|21.00|m|ftin}} |Ship draught={{convert|4.40|m|ftin}} |Ship depth= |Ship decks= |Ship deck clearance= |Ship ramps= |Ship ice class= |Ship power=*Klöckner-Humboldt-Deutz SBV 6M 628 [[diesel engine]], {{convert|1175|kW|hp}} @ 90rpm *bow thruster {{convert|136|kW|hp}} |Ship propulsion=Screw propeller |Ship speed={{convert|10|kn|km/h}} |Ship capacity=72 [[twenty-foot equivalent unit]] (1984–2008) |Ship crew= 8 |Ship notes= }} |}
The '''''Cemfjord''''' was a Cyprus-registered cargo ship which foundered in the [[Pentland Firth]] off the north-east coast of [[Scotland]] on 2 January 2015. Built as the general cargo ship '''''Margareta''''' in 1984, she was converted to carry cement in 1998 and was en route from [[Aalborg]], [[Denmark]] to [[Runcorn]], [[Cheshire]], United Kingdom when she capsized in bad weather and sank in {{convert|270|ft|m|order=flip}} of water. All eight crew were presumed lost. No bodies were recovered, and the ship has been left as a sea grave.
==Description== The ship was {{convert|83.13|m|ftin}} long overall, with a beam of {{convert|11.34|m|ftin}}. She had a draught of {{convert|4.40|m|ftin}} and a height of {{convert|21.00|m|ftin}}. The ship was assessed at {{GT|1850}},<ref name=Brise/> {{DWT|2327}},<ref name=Seanews132164/> 661 [[net tonnage|NT]].<ref name=Brise/>
She was powered by a [[KHD|Klöckner-Humboldt-Deutz]] 6M 628 [[diesel engine]] which produced {{convert|1175|kW|hp}} at 790 rpm. The engine was a [[four-stroke engine]] with six cylinders of 240mm diameter by 280mm stroke.<ref name=Scheepvaartwest/> It drove a screw propeller, which could propel her at {{convert|10|kn|km/h}}. The ship was also equipped with a 136-kilowatt (182-horsepower) [[bow thruster]].<ref name=Brise>{{cite web |url=http://www.brise.de/download/details/Cemfjord.pdf |title=CEMFJORD |publisher=Baltrader Schiffahrt |location=Hamburg |accessdate=4 January 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104162004/http://www.brise.de/download/details/Cemfjord.pdf |archivedate=4 January 2015 |df= }}</ref>
==History== The ship was built as yard number 126 by Detlef Hegemann Rolandwerft [[GmbH]], [[Bremen]], [[West Germany]]. Her keel was laid on 15 February 1984 and she was launched as the general cargo ship ''Margareta'' on 31 August. Completion was in November 1984. She was allocated the [[IMO Number]] 8403569. Her call sign was DCOG. She had a cargo capacity of 72 [[twenty-foot equivalent unit]]. ''Margareta'' was built for Thekla Schepers KG and operated under the management of MS Margareta & Co, [[Haren, Germany|Haren]], [[West Germany]]. In May 1995 she was sold to the Margareta – Shark Shipping Co NV, [[Willemstad]], [[Netherlands Antilles]] and placed under the management of Briese Schiffahrts GMBH & Co KG, [[Bremen]], Germany.<ref name=Scheepvaartwest>{{cite web |url=http://www.scheepvaartwest.be/CMS/index.php/general-cargo/1612-cemfjord-imo-8403569 |title=Cemfjord – IMO8403659 |publisher=Scheepvaartwest |accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref>
In June 1998, she was converted to a cement carrier by [[Morska Stocznia Remontowa]] S.A., [[Świnoujście]], [[Poland]]. Pneumatic equipment was installed which enabled her to self load and self discharge. She was allocated the call sign P3ZG9.<ref name=Brise/> She was owned and operated by Brise Bereederung, [[Hamburg]], Germany.<ref name=Seanews132164/>
Following an inspection at Runcorn, Cheshire, on 15 December 2013, ''Cemfjord'' was detained due to deficiencies found. The launch apparatus for her [[lifeboat (shipboard)|lifeboats]] was inoperative and her safety management did not meet the required standard. There were nine other deficiencies of a lesser nature. She was released from detention on 18 December 2013.<ref name=Shipworld>{{cite web |url=http://www.shipworld.org/casualties-archive/casualties-january-2014/ |title=CASUALTIES – JANUARY 2014 |publisher=Shipworld |date=31 January 2014 |accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref>
At 22:14 on 29 July 2014, ''Cemfjord'' ran aground in the [[Kattegat]] off [[Læsø]], Denmark. The authorities were contacted at 01:47 on 30 July and the ship was refloated later that day. Her Russian captain was subsequently convicted of being drunk in charge of the vessel. He was fined [[Danish krone|DKK 10,000]] by a Danish court. A new Polish captain was appointed to take charge of the ship.<ref name=Seanews132164>{{cite web |url=http://www.seanews.com.tr/article/ACCIDENTS/132164/Cemfjord/ |title=Drunk master ran cement carrier aground off Denmark |publisher=SeaNews Turkey |date=31 July 2014 |accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> In August 2014, a second Russian captain in command of ''Cemfjord'' was convicted by [[Stavanger District Court|a court]] in [[Stavanger]], Norway. The court sentenced him to 35 days imprisonment for steering his ship while being intoxicated, and banned him from being in charge of a ship in Norwegian waters for two years.<ref name=Seanews133696>{{cite web |url=http://www.seanews.com.tr/article/worldship/133696/Cemfjord-drunk-captain/ |title=35 days imprisonment for drunken Russian captain |publisher=SeaNews Turkey |date=29 August 2014 |accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref>
===Sinking===
On her last voyage, ''Cemfjord'' was carrying 2,000 tonnes of cement from Aalborg in Denmark to Runcorn in Cheshire and was due to arrive on 5 January 2015.<ref name=BBC30670842>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-north-east-orkney-shetland-30670842|title=Crew of eight feared lost as cargo ship Cemfjord sinks|publisher=BBC News Online|date=4 January 2015 |accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> She was last sighted at 13:00 on 2 January 2015 in the Pentland Firth. At 14:30 on 3 January,<ref name=BBC30667084>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-highlands-islands-30667084 |title=Major search after ship overturns off north of Scotland |publisher=BBC News Online |date=3 January 2015 |accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> her upturned hull was sighted {{convert|11|nmi|km}} east of the [[Pentland Skerries]] by the [[NorthLink Ferries|NorthLink]] [[ferry]] {{MV|Hrossey||2}}, which was sailing from [[Shetland]] to [[Aberdeen]]. Only the bow was visible above the waves. The ferry searched for survivors for two and a half hours pending the arrival of [[lifeboat (rescue)|lifeboats]].<ref name=WMN148569>{{cite web |url=http://worldmaritimenews.com/archives/148569/eight-missing-after-cement-carrier-sinks-off-scotland/ |title=Eight Missing after Cement Carrier Sinks off Scotland |publisher=World Maritime News |accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> No distress call had been received and the weather at the time was bad, with storm force winds. There was no trace of her eight crew, comprising seven Poles and a Filipino. The Longhope, Scrabster, Stromness and Wick lifeboats were launched. Two helicopters and an aircraft also joined the search for the missing crew members,<ref name=BBC30667084/> as did {{HMS|Somerset|F82|6}}.<ref name=Orcadian>{{cite web|url=http://www.orcadian.co.uk/2015/01/missing-crew-search-suspended/ |title=Missing crew search suspended |publisher=The Orcadian |accessdate=4 January 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104203706/http://www.orcadian.co.uk/2015/01/missing-crew-search-suspended/ |archivedate=4 January 2015 |df= }}</ref> By mid-afternoon on 4 January, the ship had sunk entirely.<ref name="DR-5-1-2015">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/cargo-ship-sinking-lifeboat-crew-4920338|title=Cargo ship sinking: Lifeboat crew fear eight men died trapped inside their ship as search fails to find them|work=Daily Record|last=Gall|first=Charlie|date=5 January 2015|accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref>
The [[Marine Accident Investigation Branch]] (MAIB) conducted an investigation into the sinking.<ref name=MAIB>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/maib-investigations-launched|title=MAIB investigators deployed to Pentland Firth and to the Solent |publisher=Marine Accident Investigation Branch |accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref> An MAIB underwater survey located the vessel on the seabed at a depth of around {{convert|270|ft|order=flip}},<ref name="PJ21-Feb-2015" /> {{convert|12|mi|km}} east of [[Muckle Skerry]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.orcadian.co.uk/2015/02/cemfjord-wreck-survey-is-complete/|title=Cemfjord wreck survey is complete|work=The Orcadian|date=10 February 2015|accessdate=29 July 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150817215351/http://www.orcadian.co.uk/2015/02/cemfjord-wreck-survey-is-complete/|archivedate=17 August 2015|df=}}</ref> The wreck was found to be intact but inverted and resting on its superstructure; no evidence was observed of structural failure.<ref name="PJ21-Feb-2015">{{cite news|url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/news/highlands/497925/no-sign-of-cemfjord-bodies-during-survey-say-investigators/|title=No sign of Cemfjord bodies during survey, say investigators|last=Candlish|first=Jane|work=The Press and Journal|location=Aberdeen|date=21 February 2015|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref> It is thought that the ''Cemfjord'' may have been overwhelmed so quickly by bad weather that the crew did not have time to evacuate.<ref name="DR-5-1-2015" /> No bodies were seen or recovered during the survey or subsequently. The ship's owner, Brise of Hamburg, has said that no attempt to raise the wreck would be made and it will be left as a sea grave.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/news/highlands/628027/families-of-seamen-lost-on-the-cemfjord-honour-loved-ones/|title=Families of seamen lost on the Cemfjord honour loved ones|last=Kerr|first=David|work=The Press and Journal|location=Aberdeen|date=4 July 2015|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>
Less than two months prior to her sinking, on 7 October 2014 ''Cemfjord'' was left with a list in the [[Pentland Firth]], after her cargo shifted. The list was corrected by ballasting the ship. Contrary to regulations, the incident was not reported to the MAIB, although an internal investigation was carried out by Brise Breederungs, the ship's managers.<ref name=Final>{{cite web |url=https://assets.digital.cabinet-office.gov.uk/media/571760fee5274a22d300001e/MAIBInvReport_8_2016.pdf |title=Report on the investigation of the capsize and sinking of the cement carrier Cemfjord in the Pentland Firth, Scotland with the loss of all eight crew on 2 and 3 January 2015 |publisher=Marine Accident Investigation Branch |date=April 2016 |accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref>
