{{refimprove|date=January 2009}}
In psychology, '''parallel processing''' is the ability of the [[brain]] to simultaneously process incoming stimuli of differing quality.<ref> {{cite journal | last=LaBerge | first=David | last2=Samuels | first2=S.Jay | title=Toward a theory of automatic information processing in reading | journal=Cognitive Psychology | publisher=Elsevier BV | volume=6 | issue=2 | year=1974 | issn=0010-0285 | doi=10.1016/0010-0285(74)90015-2 | pages=293–323 | ref=harv}}</ref> Parallel processing is a part of [[Visual perception|vision]] in that the brain divides what it sees into four components: [[color]], [[motion (physics)|motion]], [[shape]], and [[Distance|depth]]. These are individually analyzed and then compared to stored [[memory|memories]], which helps the brain identify what you are viewing.<ref>{{cite book | last=Hinton | first=Geoffrey | title=Parallel models of associative memory | publisher=Psychology Press | publication-place=New York | year=2014 | isbn=978-1-315-80799-7 | ref=harv}}</ref> The brain then combines all of these into the field of view that you see and comprehend.<ref name="Wässle2004">{{cite journal|last1=Wässle|first1=Heinz|title=Parallel processing in the mammalian retina|journal=Nature Reviews Neuroscience|volume=5|issue=10|year=2004|pages=747–757|issn=1471-003X|doi=10.1038/nrn1497}}</ref> Parallel processing has been linked, by some experimental psychologists, to the [[Stroop effect]]. This is a continual and seamless operation.

