'''Pierre-César Abeille''' (1674 - after 1733) was a French composer. Born in the [[Salon-de-Provence]] of southern France, he was baptized on 24 February 1674. He was the son of Jean Abeille, a royal notary.<ref>{{cite book|last=Grove|first=George|title=The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians|year=1980|publisher=Macmillan Publishers|location=London|isbn=9781561591749|page=9}}</ref>
From 1699 to 1700, Abeille was ''maître de chapelle'' of the primate's [[Church of St. Trophime, Arles]]. When he was succeeded by Fançois Pétouille, he was ''vicaire de choeur'' and ''maitre de musique'' at the royal parish church of [[Saint-Germain l'Auxerrois]] in Paris.<ref>{{cite book|last=Raugel|first=Félix|authorlink= Félix Raugel |title=Les maîtres français de l'orgue aux XVIIe et XVIIIe siècles|year=1961|publisher=Musicales de la Schola Cantorum et de la Procure Générale de Musique|location=Paris|oclc=642932728|pages=99–106}}</ref>
== Music == Abeille's best known work is the two volume set ''Psalms of David'', dedicated to [[Françoise d'Aubigné, Marquise de Maintenon|Madame de Maintenon]]. It is a set of 150 psalms that alternate among [[Air (music)|airs]], [[duet]]s, and [[ritornello]]s. The pieces are generally performed in a concertante style.<ref>{{cite book|last=Grove|first=George|title=The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians|year=1980|publisher=Macmillan Publishers|location=London|isbn=9781561591749|page=10}}</ref>
